---
import Base from '../../layouts/Base.astro';
import {
  OPERATING_QUESTION,
  VERDICT,
  ASYMMETRY,
  PROBES,
  V02_PROBES,
  DEFENSES,
  type ProbeStatus,
} from '../../data/frame-construction';
import { REGISTERED_FUTURES } from '../../data/registered-futures';
import { VERDICT_PROTOCOL } from '../../data/verdict-protocol';

const statusColor: Record<ProbeStatus, string> = {
  failing: 'var(--color-verdict)',
  contested: 'hsl(34 96% 60%)',
  untested: 'var(--color-muted)',
};
const statusLabel: Record<ProbeStatus, string> = {
  failing: 'Failing',
  contested: 'Contested',
  untested: 'Untested',
};
---

<Base
  title="The Einstein Test — pathtoAGI"
  description="The operating question, operationalized: six frame-construction probes with contamination defenses and a deliberate scoring asymmetry. The Observatory's distinctive instrument."
>
  <section class="max-w-3xl">
    <p class="eyebrow">The moat · frame construction</p>
    <h1 class="display mt-4 text-4xl sm:text-5xl">The Einstein Test</h1>
    <p class="lede mt-6">{OPERATING_QUESTION}</p>
    <p class="prose mt-6">
      The question is not the Observatory's prediction — it is its calibration
      instrument. Anyone can score a benchmark. The distinctive thing this
      record does is ask whether a system can perform <strong>frame
      construction</strong>: notice that the inherited ontology is wrong, find
      the representation no prompt handed it, and derive consequences that
      survive contact with reality. General relativity is the best-documented
      act of large-scale frame construction in the history of science. That is
      why it is the ruler.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The asymmetry -->
  <section class="mt-12 grid gap-4 sm:grid-cols-2">
    <div
      class="surface p-6"
      style="border-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-verdict) 45%, var(--color-line));"
    >
      <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-verdict);">
        Weak performance
      </p>
      <p class="serif mt-2 text-xl" style="color: var(--color-ink);">
        {ASYMMETRY.weak}
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="surface p-6">
      <p class="eyebrow">Strong performance</p>
      <p class="serif mt-2 text-xl" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
        {ASYMMETRY.strong}
      </p>
    </div>
    <p class="sm:col-span-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
      This asymmetry is the point. The suite is falsifier-rich: a system that
      fails despite having read the entire Einstein corpus has failed. A system
      that passes has passed a <em>weaker</em> test than the question actually
      names — and the Observatory says so, rather than declaring victory.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- The six probes -->
  <section class="mt-14">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">The suite · v0.1 · six probes</p>
        <h2 class="serif mt-1 text-2xl">Einstein's path, time-sliced</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
        {PROBES.length} designed · 1 self-run
      </p>
    </div>
    <ol class="mt-5 space-y-3">
      {
        PROBES.map((p) => (
          <li class="surface p-5">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
              <span
                class="mono text-sm font-medium"
                style="color: var(--color-ink);"
              >
                {p.id}
              </span>
              <span class="serif text-lg" style="color: var(--color-ink);">
                {p.label}
              </span>
              {p.adversarial && (
                <span
                  class="mono rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[0.65rem] uppercase tracking-wider"
                  style="background: var(--color-surface-2); color: hsl(34 96% 60%);"
                >
                  adversarial
                </span>
              )}
              <span class="mono ml-auto text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
                {p.timeSlice}
              </span>
              <span
                class="mono inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-xs"
                style={`color: ${statusColor[p.status]};`}
              >
                <span
                  class="inline-block h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full"
                  style={`background: ${statusColor[p.status]};`}
                />
                {statusLabel[p.status]}
              </span>
            </div>
            <p class="serif mt-2" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
              {p.frame}
            </p>
            <p class="mt-1.5 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
              {p.note}
            </p>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- v0.2 non-physics probes -->
  <section class="mt-14">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">The suite · v0.2 · lower contamination floor</p>
        <h2 class="serif mt-1 text-2xl">Beyond physics</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
        {V02_PROBES.length} designed · 0 run
      </p>
    </div>
    <p class="prose mt-4 max-w-3xl">
      Physics is where the contamination floor is highest — every system has read
      the whole Einstein corpus. v0.2 moves into domains where a real
      frame-construction move can be time-sliced with less saturation, so a
      <em>weak</em> score keeps its force. Each probe names a documented
      historical frame break and the scaffolding a run must remove. All are
      honestly untested until a logged run exists.
    </p>
    <ol class="mt-5 space-y-3">
      {
        V02_PROBES.map((p) => (
          <li class="surface p-5">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
              <span class="mono text-sm font-medium" style="color: var(--color-ink);">
                {p.id}
              </span>
              <span class="serif text-lg" style="color: var(--color-ink);">
                {p.label}
              </span>
              <span
                class="mono rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[0.65rem] uppercase tracking-wider"
                style="background: var(--color-surface-2); color: var(--color-accent);"
              >
                {p.domain}
              </span>
              {p.adversarial && (
                <span
                  class="mono rounded px-1.5 py-0.5 text-[0.65rem] uppercase tracking-wider"
                  style="background: var(--color-surface-2); color: hsl(34 96% 60%);"
                >
                  adversarial
                </span>
              )}
              <span class="mono ml-auto text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
                {p.timeSlice}
              </span>
              <span
                class="mono inline-flex items-center gap-1.5 text-xs"
                style={`color: ${statusColor[p.status]};`}
              >
                <span
                  class="inline-block h-1.5 w-1.5 rounded-full"
                  style={`background: ${statusColor[p.status]};`}
                />
                {statusLabel[p.status]}
              </span>
            </div>
            <p class="serif mt-2" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
              {p.frame}
            </p>
            <p class="mt-1.5 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
              {p.note}
            </p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
              <span class="mono uppercase tracking-wider">Contamination floor · </span>
              {p.contaminationFloor}
            </p>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- Contamination defenses -->
  <section class="mt-14 max-w-3xl">
    <p class="eyebrow">Why a pass is only an upper bound</p>
    <h2 class="serif mt-1 text-2xl">The contamination defenses</h2>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      Every frontier system has read most of the Einstein literature. A naïve
      test would measure recall, not frame construction. The suite answers with
      seven defenses — and the standing admission that they are imperfect, which
      is exactly why weak scores count for more than strong ones.
    </p>
    <ul class="mt-5 space-y-2.5">
      {
        DEFENSES.map((d, i) => (
          <li class="flex gap-3">
            <span
              class="mono mt-0.5 text-xs"
              style="color: var(--color-accent);"
            >
              {String(i + 1).padStart(2, '0')}
            </span>
            <span class="text-sm" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
              {d}
            </span>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </section>

  <!-- v0.3 prospective probes -->
  <section class="mt-14">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">The suite · v0.3 · zero contamination floor</p>
        <h2 class="serif mt-1 text-2xl">Registered futures</h2>
      </div>
      <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
        {REGISTERED_FUTURES.length} registered · 0 attempted
      </p>
    </div>
    <p class="prose mt-4 max-w-3xl">
      Historical probes are contaminated forever — every corpus contains the
      answers. These have a contamination floor of <em>zero</em>: unsolved
      problems where the resolution is expected to require a frame move. Minds
      attempt the frame now; the attempt is timestamp-anchored; reality grades
      it when the field settles. Slow, and incorruptible.
    </p>
    <ol class="mt-5 space-y-3">
      {
        REGISTERED_FUTURES.map((rf) => (
          <li class="surface p-5">
            <div class="flex flex-wrap items-center gap-3">
              <span class="mono text-sm font-medium" style="color: var(--color-ink);">{rf.id}</span>
              <span class="mono ml-auto text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">horizon {rf.horizonDate}</span>
              <span class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{rf.status}</span>
            </div>
            <p class="serif mt-2" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">{rf.problem}</p>
            <p class="mt-1.5 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{rf.whyFrameConstruction}</p>
            <p class="mt-2 text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
              <span class="mono uppercase tracking-wider">Resolution · </span>{rf.resolutionCriterion}
            </p>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
    <div class="surface mt-4 p-5" style="border-color: color-mix(in oklab, var(--color-affirm) 30%, var(--color-line));">
      <p class="eyebrow" style="color: var(--color-affirm);">world-001 · executed 2026-07-02 · zero contamination</p>
      <p class="mt-2 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-ink-dim);">
        Two frontier minds (Claude Fable 5, GPT-5.5) recovered the exact hidden
        law of a world generated the same day and predicted all 72 held-out
        states — attempts anchored before the reveal, graded mechanically. The
        strongest raw result on the record. It did <em>not</em> move the verdict:
        the frame family was disclosed and code was allowed, so scaffold-ablation
        (gate vg-3) is unmet. See the evidence ledger
        (<span class="mono">cce-2026-07-02-fcs-synth-world-001</span>),
        precedent <span class="mono">P-9</span>, and the anchored attempts +
        <span class="mono">REVEAL.md</span> in the repository.
      </p>
    </div>
    <p class="mt-4 max-w-3xl text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
      The next world (v0.4) withholds the frame family, goes nonlinear, ablates
      code, and adds a human baseline and independent scorer — the conditions
      under which a strong result would begin to bear on the architectural gap.
    </p>
  </section>

  <!-- Verdict-change protocol -->
  <section class="mt-14 max-w-3xl">
    <div class="flex items-baseline justify-between gap-4">
      <h2 class="serif text-2xl">What would change the verdict</h2>
      <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-faint);">
        protocol v{VERDICT_PROTOCOL.version} · pinned {VERDICT_PROTOCOL.pinnedAt}
      </p>
    </div>
    <p class="prose mt-4">
      Pre-registered before it is needed, so the moment of passage — or its
      refusal — cannot be gamed by the instrument itself. <strong>All five
      gates are required;</strong> by precedent, any one alone is an anecdote.
    </p>
    <ol class="mt-5 space-y-2.5">
      {
        VERDICT_PROTOCOL.positiveGates.map((g) => (
          <li class="surface-quiet p-4">
            <p class="mono text-xs" style="color: var(--color-accent);">{g.id} · {g.gate}</p>
            <p class="mt-1 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">{g.standard}</p>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
    <p class="mt-4 text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
      Amendment requires a revision-log entry, an anchored release, and a Press
      notice — and a verdict moved under an amended protocol must say so.
      Governance details on <a href="/governance/" class="link-accent">/governance/</a>.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-14">
    <div class="surface-quiet p-6">
      <p class="eyebrow">Current reading</p>
      <p class="serif mt-2 text-2xl" style="color: var(--color-ink);">
        {VERDICT.answer}
      </p>
      <p class="mt-2 max-w-2xl text-sm" style="color: var(--color-muted);">
        One real run exists: FCS-1 was executed 2026-07-01 against two minds
        under a 1906 time-slice. Both passed at face value — and per the
        asymmetry that pass is an <em>upper bound</em>, not evidence of frame
        construction, because the Einstein corpus saturates their training.
        FCS-1 is therefore <em>contested</em>; the other five probes remain
        honestly <em>untested</em>. The verdict rests on the public evidence
        ledger, unmoved. The full run record — prompt, both transcripts, and
        grading — is published at
        <a href="/experiments/fcs-1-2026-07-01/" class="hover:underline" style="color: var(--color-ink);">/experiments/fcs-1-2026-07-01/</a>. (A
        2026-07-01 self-audit retracted earlier claims that implied runs had
        occurred before any did.)
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
